Are you using a P100 ? I think the test failures you are experiencing is not because of the CUDA version.

Please see https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5914 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4805

I am using a RTX 3090 and tried to compile with CUDA 11.0, 11.1 and 11.2 (on Ubuntu 20.10).
None of those compiles.
I can't test CUDA 10.X as advised in the PRs because it doesn't support 30XX GPUs.

Moreover, few days before ORT 1.6 has been released (around 12/08/2020), I successfully compiled `master` branch with CUDA 11.1.
Of course, I cleaned/deleted everything and have no idea of which commit it was.

The wheel it produces and which works well for inference is available under this [link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1LlbRNUxUrdc5YCy84L6IJZB9RUW2ikCa/view?usp=sharing). May be you can retrieve the exact commit and guess which PR changes the test behaviors?

It seems the command line I was using was not right (found in some other issues + https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/dockerfiles/Dockerfile.cuda):
```
CUDACXX=/usr/local/cuda-11.1/bin/nvcc ./build.sh --config Release --build_wheel --parallel --use_cuda --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda-11.1 --cudnn_home /usr/local/cuda-11.1
```
The difference is the path to `CUDNN`.
With the command line above, it compiles `master` branch.

> It seems the command line I was using was not right (found in some other issues + https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/dockerfiles/Dockerfile.cuda):

> ```
> 
> The difference is the path to `CUDNN`.
> With the command line above, it compiles `master` branch.
